<p>Technologies like gamete cloning, when mature enough, may permit individuals to select for IQ enhancing alleles, but would only realistically be able to raise the IQ of offspring by a point or two at best (Lee, 2010).</p>
<ul>
<li>Lee, J. J. (2010). Review of intelligence and how to get it: Why schools and cultures count, R.E. Nisbett, Norton, New York, NY (2009). ISBN: 9780393065053. Personality and Individual Differences, 48, 247-255 [count me skeptical, given the existing genetic variation‚Ä¶ we should be able to get more than a point or two]</li>
</ul>
<p>‚Ä¶it is indicated that the Flynn effect hasn‚Äôt really started to take off in these nations, but that it has the potential to do so (Wicherts, Dolan, Carlson, &amp; van der Maas, 2010). This is evidenced by observations of a nascent Flynn effect in South Africa (te Nijenhuis, Murphy, &amp; van Eeden, 2011), Kenya (Daley, Whaley, Sigman, Espinosa, &amp; Neumann, 2003), Dominica (Meisenberg et al., 2005), Saudi Arabia (Batterjee, 2011) and elsewhere. It is entirely possible therefore that many of the less developed nations are entering into the early stages of an ‚Äúenhanced growth‚Äù phase in the Flynn effect, a consequence of which might be significant decreases in poverty, such as is currently occurring in Africa (Sala-i-Martin &amp; Pinkovskiy, 2010).</p>
<ul>
<li>Wicherts, J. M., Dolan, C. V., Carlson, J. S., &amp; van der Maas, H. L. J. (2010). ‚ÄúRaven‚Äôs test performance of sub-Saharan Africans: Mean level, psychometric properties, and the Flynn effect‚Äù. Learning and Individual Differences, 20, 135-151</li>
<li>te Nijenhuis, J., Murphy, R., &amp; van Eeden, R. (2011). ‚ÄúThe Flynn effect in South Africa‚Äù. Intelligence, 36, 456-467</li>
<li>Daley, T. C., Whaley, S. E., Sigman, M. D., Espinosa, M. P., &amp; Neumann, C. (2003). ‚ÄúIQ on the rise: the Flynn effect in rural Kenyan children‚Äù. Psychological Science, 14, 215-219</li>
<li>Meisenberg, G., Lawless, E., Lambert, E., &amp; Newton, A. (2005). ‚ÄúThe Flynn effect in the Caribbean: Generational change of cognitive test performance in Dominica‚Äù. Mankind Quarterly, 46, 29-69.</li>
