<li id="fn1"><p>An example: Singapore‚Äôs government reportedly expects half the population to hold at least a bachelor‚Äôs degree by 2020. This is surely doable, just as the US could expect half its population to graduate high school, just like industrializing countries can shift their proletariat to the cities &amp; factories. But this is a trick you can do only once! You can‚Äôt have half your population join the first half in the cities, leaving 1% to handle the mechanized agriculture - for tremendous economic growth - and then have <em>another</em> half move into the cities to keep the growth going, because there is no third half. Similarly for degrees. Bachelor‚Äôs, perhaps; master‚Äôs, maybe; but PhD? Not with existing populations or gene pools.<a href="#fnref1">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
